{"title_page": "Shirley Knight", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shirley Knight\n| image              = Shirley Knight 1960s.JPG\n| caption            = Shirley Knight in 1963\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1936|07|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Goessel, Kansas]]\n| othername          = Shirley Knight Hopkins\n| alma_mater         = [[Wichita State University]]\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 1959\u2013present\n| spouse             = [[Gene Persson]] (m. 1959, div. 69)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117987838.html?categoryId=25&cs=1|title=Gene Persson dies at 74|work=Variety|date=June 20, 2008|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> <br>[[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]] (m. 1969, d. 1998)\n| children           = 2, including [[Kaitlin Hopkins]]\n}}\n\n'''Shirley Knight Hopkins''' (born July 5, 1936) is an American actress who has appeared in more than 50 feature films, television movies, television series, and Broadway and Off-Broadway productions in her career playing leading and character roles. She is a member of the [[Actors Studio]].\n\nKnight has been nominated twice for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]: for ''[[The Dark at the Top of the Stairs (film)|The Dark at the Top of the Stairs]]'' (1960) and ''[[Sweet Bird of Youth (film)|Sweet Bird of Youth]]'' (1962).<ref>{{cite web |title=(\"Shirley Knight\" search results) |url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/search/results |website=Academy Awards Database |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> In the 1960s, she had leading roles in a number of Hollywood movies such as ''[[The Couch (film)|The Couch]]'' (1962), ''[[House of Women]]'' (1962), ''[[The Group (film)|The Group]]'' (1966), ''[[The Counterfeit Killer]]'' (1968), and ''[[The Rain People]]'' (1969). She received the [[Volpi Cup for Best Actress]] for her role in the British film ''[[Dutchman (film)|Dutchman]]'' (1966).\n\nIn 1976, Knight won a [[Tony Award]] for her performance in ''Kennedy's Children''. In later years, she played supporting roles in many films, include ''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]'' (1981), ''[[As Good as It Gets]]'' (1997), ''[[Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood (film)|Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood]]'' (2002), and ''[[Grandma's Boy (2006 film)|Grandma's Boy]]'' (2006). For her performances on television, Knight was nominated eight times for a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] (winning three), and she has received a [[Golden Globe Award]].\n\n==Early life==\nKnight was born in Goessel, Kansas, the daughter of Virginia (n\u00e9e Webster) and Noel Johnson Knight, an oil company executive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Shirley-Knight.html|title=Shirley Knight Biography|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> She spent her young life in Mitchell, Kansas, and later lived in Lyons, Kansas, where she graduated from high school. She began studying to be an opera singer at age 11.\n\nAt the age of 14, she wrote a short story that was published in a national magazine. Knight later attended Phillips University and Wichita State University. After studying at the Pasadena Theatre School she began her film career in 1959. She then went to New York and began her theatre career. She trained in acting with [[Jeff Corey]], [[Erwin Piscator]], [[Lee Strasberg]], and [[Uta Hagen]] at [[HB Studio]].<ref>[https://hbstudio.org/about-hb-studio/alumni/ HB Studio Alumni]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribute.ca/people/shirley-knight/1727|title=Shirley Knight biography and filmography - Shirley Knight movies|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shirleyknight.org/biography.html|title=Shirley Knight's Biography|website=www.shirleyknight.org|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Alan Arkin - Kudirka - 1978.jpg|thumb|Knight with [[Alan Arkin]] in ''[[The Defection of Simas Kudirka]]'' (1978)]]\nKnight's feature films include ''[[The Group (film)|The Group]]'' (1966), ''[[Dutchman (film)|The Dutchman]]'' (1966), ''[[Petulia]]'' (1968), ''[[The Rain People]]'' (1969), ''[[Juggernaut (1974 film)|Juggernaut]]'' (1974), ''[[As Good as It Gets]]'' (1997), and ''[[Elevator (2011 film)|Elevator]]'' (2011), in which she plays one of several people trapped in a Wall Street elevator with a bomber.\n\nKnight was cast in 1958 and 1959 as Mrs. Newcomb in 20 of the 29 episodes of the television series ''[[Buckskin (TV series)|Buckskin]]'', with [[Tom Nolan (actor)|Tom Nolan]], [[Sally Brophy]], and [[Mike Road]]. She became a [[Warner Brothers Television]] contract star who while on breaks filming movies appeared in television series such as ''[[Maverick (TV series)|Maverick]]'', ''[[Bourbon Street Beat]]'', ''[[Sugarfoot]]'', ''[[Cheyenne (TV series)|Cheyenne]]'', and ''[[The Roaring 20s (TV series)|The Roaring 20s]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://classictvhistory.wordpress.com/2010/07/01/an-interview-with-shirley-knight|title=An Interview With Shirley Knight|date=July 1, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA life member of [[The Actors Studio]],<ref>{{cite book|quote=|first=David |last=Garfield|title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|url=https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf|url-access=registration|year=1980|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf/page/278 278]|chapter=Appendix: Life Members of The Actors Studio as of January 1980}}</ref> Knight's stage credits include ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'' (1964), ''[[We Have Always Lived in the Castle]]'' (1966), ''Kennedy's Children'' (1975), which earned her the [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Play]],<ref name=\"ta\">{{cite web |title=(\"Shirley Knight\" search results) |url=https://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/history/pastwinners/tonys_results.html?fname=Shirley&lname=Knight&show=&award=Category&year=Year |website=Tony Awards |accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> and ''[[A Lovely Sunday for Creve Coeur]]'' (1979).\n\nShe was nominated for the [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play]] twice, for ''[[Landscape of the Body]]'' and ''The Young Man from Atlanta'', for which she received another Tony nomination.<ref name=ta/> She also appeared in ''Come Back, Come Back, Wherever You Are'', (2009) an original play by playwright [[Arthur Laurents]].\n\nHer television credits include ''[[Target: The Corruptors!]]'', ''[[The Eleventh Hour (1962 TV series)|The Eleventh Hour]]'', ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'' (\"[[The Man Who Was Never Born]]\"),  ''[[The Reporter (TV series)|The Reporter]]'', ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'', ''[[The Invaders]]'', ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]'', ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', ''[[thirtysomething (TV series)|Thirtysomething]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', ''[[L.A. Law]]'',  ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'', ''[[Maggie Winters]]'', ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'',  ''[[House (TV series)|House M.D.]]'', ''[[Crossing Jordan]]'', ''[[Cold Case]]'', and ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'', among others.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}  Shirley Knight also appeared in Barnaby Jones; episode titled, \"Fantasy of Fear\"(02/25/1975).\n\nShe has appeared in various television movies, including ''[[Playing for Time (film)|Playing For Time]]'' and ''[[Indictment: The McMartin Trial]]''. For the latter, she won both the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress - Miniseries or a Movie|Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie]] and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role in a Series, Mini-Series or Motion Picture Made for Television]]. Her guest performance in ''[[thirtysomething (TV series)|thirtysomething]]'' earned her a 1988 Emmy for Best Guest Performer in a Drama Series. She won Emmy in 1995 for her guest performance in the ''[[NYPD Blue]]'' episode \"Large Mouth Bass\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/bios/shirley-knight|title=Shirley Knight - Television Academy|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in the first segment of ''[[If These Walls Could Talk]]''. She also had a recurring role on ''[[Desperate Housewives]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/shirley-knight-plays-a-desperate-former-housewife-in-cycling-past-the-matterhorn-opening-sept-29-com-128318|title=Shirley Knight Plays a Desperate Former Housewife in Cycling Past the Matterhorn, Opening Sept. 29 - Playbill|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKnight was married to American actor and producer [[Gene Persson]] from 1959 until their divorce in 1969. They had one child, actress [[Kaitlin Hopkins]] (born February 1, 1964).\n\nHer second marriage was to English writer [[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]] from 1969 until his death in 1998. She and Hopkins raised her daughter with Persson together. They had one child, elementary school teacher Sophie C. Hopkins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/news/actors-dialogue-shirley-knight-kaitlin-hopkins|title=ACTORS' DIALOGUE:  Shirley Knight & Kaitlin Hopkins|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1959  \n| ''[[Five Gates to Hell]]''\n| Sister Maria\n| \n|-\n| 1960 \n| ''[[Ice Palace (film)|Ice Palace]]''\n| Grace Kennedy\n| \n|- \n| 1960\n| ''[[The Dark at the Top of the Stairs (film)|The Dark at the Top of the Stairs]]''\n| Reenie Flood\n| Nominated\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actress]]\n|-\n| 1962 \n| ''[[The Couch (film)|The Couch]]''\n